#Text=West Bank
#Text=The West Bank is an area located between in the Middle East between Israel and Jordan , to the north of the Dead Sea .
#Text=It forms the larger half of the semi-autonomous Palestinian Territories , the smaller being the Gaza Strip .
#Text=De facto control on the ground tends to be Israeli , Palestinian ( Fatah since the Hamas takeover of Gaza ) or some degree of joint sovereignty .
#Text=Be prepared for that to affect your travels and to come upon checkpoints and signs barring Israeli citizens from entering certain areas .
#Text=Cities
#Text=In each group , cities are listed from north to south :
#Text=Mixed
#Text=( الخليل/חברון ) In the southern West Bank , a holy city due to the presence of the Cave of the Patriarchs .
#Text=There is a large Palestinian majority , with a few hundred Jews living in the city center , and a few thousand more in the suburb/settlement of Kiryat Arba .
#Text=Palestinian
#Text=( جنين /ג'נין ) – the West Bank 's northernmost city , only 26km from Nazareth .
#Text=Its name 's meaning is The spring of gardens .
#Text=( طولكرم/טולכרם )
#Text=( نابلس/ שׁכם ) – considered the commercial capital of the West Bank , and known for its old city , its furniture trade and the delicious kunafa/kenafeh
#Text=( قلقيلية/קלקיליה )
#Text=( رام الله/רמאללה ) – the administrative capital of the West Bank and temporary host to the PNA , Ramallah is a magnet for Palestinians seeking work as well as foreign activists
#Text=( أريحا/יריחו ) – the " Oldest City in the World " , around 400m below sea level and great starting point for the Dead Sea

#Text=( بيت لحم/בית לחם ) – an ancient city much like many others in the West Bank , Bethlehem is also the site of Christian holy places such as the Church of the Nativity and a Jewish holy site as the City of David ; it is a UNESCO World Heritage Site
#Text=Major Israeli settlements
#Text=The following settlements are of interest for tourists :
#Text=( اريئيل/אריאל )
#Text=( معاليه أدوميم/מעלה אדומים )
#Text=( جوش عتصيون/גוש עציון ) including Efrat
#Text=Large settlements of zero interest to tourists include Modiin Ilit and Beitar Ilit .
#Text=Other destinations
#Text=– the lowest place on earth , with natural and historic sites as well as beaches and resorts .
#Text=–
#Text=great for hiking and nature
#Text=Understand
#Text=This area is known as the West Bank because it lies on the western bank of the Jordan River .
#Text=This part of the world is steeped in biblical history and contains many sites of religious and archaeological significance .
#Text=It has been under Israeli administration since 1967 with future status uncertain and still to be resolved , between Israel and the Palestinian National Authority ( PNA ) .
#Text=Historically and among some parts of Israeli society , especially those to the right politically
#Text=the area has also been known as Judaea/Samaria .
#Text=About 2.5 million Palestinians and 400,000 Israelis live in the West Bank ( not including East Jerusalem ) .

#Text=As far as the traveller is concerned , Jewish and Arab sites in the West Bank are essentially separate travel destinations , since Jews and Arabs have separate bus networks , and rental cars can generally be used in either Arab cities or Jewish settlements but not both .
#Text=The West Bank did not exist as a concept before 1949 .
#Text=Its border is the cease-fire line between Israeli and Jordanian troops in 1949 .

#Text=Even though both sides specified at the time that it was not a permanent border , nevertheless , nowadays much of the world assumes that the border between Israel and a future Palestinian state will be based on this line .
#Text=In 1967 , due to the Six-Day War , the West Bank came under Israeli control .
#Text=Israel did not annex the West Bank ( except for East Jerusalem ) due to its large Palestinian population , but Israelis did establish civilian settlements in the West Bank .

#Text=West Bank Palestinians have often resisted the Israeli occupation , most notably in the First Intifada of the late 1980s , which however also had aspects of a civil war , targeting Palestinians seen as too pro-Israel almost as much as Israelis .
#Text=The Oslo Accords in 1993 began the " peace process " and established Palestinian autonomy in parts of the West Bank .
#Text=This autonomy was extended in several steps in the 1990s , but in 2000 the Second Intifada broke out and negotiations halted .
#Text=Since then , there have been some attempts at negotiations , but no more concrete progress towards an agreement .
#Text=Around 2002 , Israel reentered the autonomous West Bank cities in order to wipe out terror cells that were carrying out bombings in Israel .
#Text=In 2005 Israel withdrew its troops and settlers from the Gaza Strip , but they remain in the West Bank .
#Text=A year after the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza , Hamas won the Palestinian elections and subsequently took de facto control of the Gaza strip , while Fatah continues to control the west bank .
#Text=In Israeli political discourse the example of the Gaza withdrawal is often brought up as an argument against concessions or withdrawal , especially if done unilaterally .
#Text=The West Bank is divided into three noncontiguous areas based on the Oslo Accords :
#Text=Area A ( 18 % of land ) - Full Palestinian military and civil control , but Israel sometimes launches raids here to capture suspected terrorists .
#Text=This includes most Palestinian cities .
#Text=Area B ( 21 % of land ) - Israeli military control , Palestinian civil control .
#Text=This includes most Palestinian villages and the farmland between them .
#Text=Area C ( 61 % of land ) - Full Israeli control .
#Text=This includes uninhabited areas , all Israeli settlements , and most major roads .
#Text=Just 4 % of West Bank Palestinians live in Area C.
#Text=There are no fences or other physical boundaries between areas A , B , and C.
#Text=However , the Israeli military has put checkpoints on many roads , generally at crossings between Area C and areas A or B.
#Text=Because areas A and B are noncontiguous , Palestinians going from place to place often have to transverse these checkpoints .
#Text=Israel 's West Bank barrier ( physically a wall and a fence depending on where you are , and labeled by either term depending on political sympathies ) is entirely within Area C.
#Text=Climate
#Text=Temperate ; temperature and precipitation vary with altitude , warm to hot summers , cool to mild winters .
#Text=Terrain
#Text=Mostly rugged dissected upland , very hilly and mountainous , heavy vegetation is common in many places .
#Text=lowest point : Dead Sea -408 m
#Text=highest point : Tall Asur
#Text=1,022 m
